# Git Commit Conventions

- Commit messages MUST be a single line. No multi-line bodies, no bullet lists, no long descriptions.
- Use conventional commit prefixes: `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`, `refactor:`, `docs:`, `style:`, `test:`.
- Keep the message under 80 characters when possible.
- Use `-m "message"` directly, never a HEREDOC or multi-paragraph body.

```bash
# Good
git commit -m "chore: add biome linting and pre-commit hooks"
git commit -m "fix: resolve null check in game engine"
git commit -m "feat: add tournament mode to exploding kittens"

# Bad - never do this
git commit -m "chore: add biome linting

- Added @biomejs/biome for linting
- Added lefthook for pre-commit hooks
- Fixed 68 button type errors
..."
```
